      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">S. Yarra ¶  9/10/95. ¶  ¶ It is very kind of you and Mrs McComas, to invite me to your hospitable home […]...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">95.10.09</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To [...] McComas</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M1, Library, Royal Botanic Garden Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Unless this was a partial draft, a letter may not have been sent, as the MS was found wrapped around a fruit specimen of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Eucalyptus drepanophylla</seg> (MEL 1607138). It is annotated by unknown: 'FvM Cape Rive (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">sic</seg>) Queensland 1895 S. Johnson'.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The correspondent may have been Robert B. W. McComas, son-in-law of Dr William and Mrs Jane Cutts, having married Ethel Jane Cutts in December 1893 (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 1 January 1894, p. 1). However, no explicit evidence has been found that M maintained his contacts with the Cutts family after the Ladies' Leichhardt Search Committee became inactive and M asked Dr Cutts to explain his views on planting school grounds with native plants (M to W. Cutts, 24 April 1872).</p>
               </note>S. Yarra<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Melbourne.</p>
               </note> 9/10/95.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is very kind of you and Mrs McComas, to invite me to your hospitable home […]<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Text breaks off in the middle of the page, without valediction.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
         </div>
